{
  "_description": "FEEDBACK OPTION A — price-elastic baseline (within-clearing feedback). Two scenarios share an identical market and a steadily TIGHTENING cap (480 → 330 Mt). 'Fixed Baseline (inelastic)' is the classic partial-equilibrium tool: BAU emissions are exogenous, so as the cap bites the carbon price escalates (≈123 → ≈172). 'Price-Elastic Baseline' sets reference_carbon_price = 55 and gives each participant output_price_elasticity > 0, so carbon-intensive ACTIVITY (and hence the baseline) contracts when the price runs above the reference: E_base(P) = E0 · max(0, 1 − ε·(P − P_ref)/P_ref). This 'demand destruction' channel is solved INSIDE market clearing each period — the equilibrium price and the activity level are found jointly. The result: the same tightening cap produces a much flatter, lower price path (≈82 → ≈101) because firms cut output rather than pay an ever-higher price. Compare 'Equilibrium Carbon Price' and the per-participant 'Initial Emissions' (which now reflects the price-scaled, realised activity) across the two scenarios. Set ε = 0 (or reference_carbon_price = 0) to recover the inelastic baseline exactly. NOTE: this is reduced-form OWN-PRICE activity response — still partial equilibrium, with no cross-sector reallocation, income effects, or energy-market closure (for those, see Option B coupling).",
